It's not just furries, it's nearly all webcomics. And despite webcomics growing immensely in quality since they first became a thing, this never changed. It mostly comes down to authors being amateurs who seem to let the infinite canvas of the internet convince them that they need to include every minute detail in their stories. They don't cut anything, they don't plan, and they sure as fuck know nothing about pacing. And with comics, the available space is extremely limited. You have to be ruthless. Every panel has to have a function. Yet most webcomics meander. And more than the tendency of artists to abandon their comics, or the often dodgy art and writing, it's this that made me eventually stop being an obsessive reader of webcomics. Most of them simply can't get to the point. I read one recently, Rising Sand. Great, if peculiar, art, very interesting world building. Still took a few years to start its basic plot. It's not been a bad read, but goddamn, you can't take literal years to introduce characters and give a little background on your main character. You do that while the plot is already underway.

Most webcomic writers need editors with experience in comics.

Anonymous Fri 04 Feb 2022 15:12:51 No.45284318 Report
Quoted By: >>45292195
>>45283409
Yeah, but that's part of the pacing issue. Even if I'm going through the archives, if there's a comic where the characters spend a year's worth of updates on a boat or something, that's still 52 pages. If they're big pages, that's an entire Franco-Belgian comic album. I think it's that lack of a definitive, clear deadline for the narrative that leads to so many webcomic artists to lavish pages and pages on useless, boring crap. If you have prodigious output, you can maybe do that. Endtown could efford some meanderings, with its insane (and literally unhealthy) page-a-day updating schedula. And even that was fairly tightly written compared to other webcomics until it started suffering from the seemingly unavoidable webcomic bloat.

I still love the medium, but it's clear that there's a hidden skill to the pacing of a comic, that no-one ever seems to talk about. Maybe it's even worse for webcomics, because reasonably an author would never want them to end. Audiences seem attracted to the comic itself, so ending a comic at any point is basically tossing your job into the trash.

Anonymous Sat 05 Feb 2022 00:04:22 No.45294185 Report
Quoted By: >>45297425
>>45292195
Theoretically webcomic artists have just as much freedom to draft and plan, with the only difference being that they release their pages incrementally. Webcomics can, and often do, go on hiatus for the artist to figure out their next step. Story bloat is no doubt a planning issue, but it's not like planning is impossible for webcomic authors. Neither are they committed once they actually start a chapter. Even just throwing up your hands and doing a hard cut would be better in a lot of cases than continuing with irrelevant content.

>Also I disagree with all authors not wanting their series to end
That means webcomics. I'm well aware that professional artists and writers finish projects and move to new ones. But the typical webcomic author does only their own webcomic, with the exception of a few wealthy/unwise writers who commission artists to churn out their comics. This is also where the self-employed nature of the webcomic artist comes in: There's no company to guarantee continued employment after the end of a project. The project is the employment, and ending a webcomic that's already bringing in the bacon is basically a massive risk with potentially very little gain.
